    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Marcia Federbush was born in Newark, New Jersey on May 25, 1934. In 1956 she married Paul Federbush. Federbush received a B.A. in Psychology from New York University and afterwards earned her Mastersâ€™ in Education in Elementary Education from Rutgers University. She also studied Organic Chemistry at Harvard University. In 1970 she began her studies in Systematic Botany and Education at the University of Michigan.</p>
      <p>Federbush advocated for the same athletic seasons for males and females. She was a prolific writer and conducted the first study of sex discrimination in a public school, entitled "Let them Aspire! A Plea and Proposal for Equality of Opportunity for Males and Females in the Ann Arbor Public Schools." Federbush actively engaged in Title IX debates and wrote many articles concerning its enforcement. She filed the first Title IX complaint against a university (University of Michigan), for "Gross Discrimination against Women in Athletics." Federbush served on various boards, including the Michigan Project on Equal Education Rights (PEER) from 1979-1984 and the advisory committee of The Sports Project Referral and Information Network (SPRINT). The SPRINT project was a part of the Women's Equity Action League (WEAL) that collected and distributed information on women and girls in sports. In 1988 Federbush was inducted into The Michigan Women's Hall of Fame for her efforts towards gender equality in education, athletics, and the workplace.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The collection contains mostly letters, articles, reports, and essays concerning equality among the sexes. Although most of the collection contains work by Federbush, there are many parts to the collection that were not written by her but may have served as inspiration for her own projects. Throughout the collection, if a folder is not specifically labeled "by Federbush" then there are mixtures of items written by different people contained in the folder. The collection is divided into three series: Equality in Education, Equality in Employment, and Equality in Athletics.</p>
    </scopecontent>
